To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has a slash command to ban users, you'll need to follow these steps:

1. Set up a new Discord application and bot on the Discord Developer Portal.
2. Install the required dependencies in your project (`discord.js` and `@discordjs/rest`).
3. Create the slash command.
4. Implement the command logic in your bot.

Here's a basic example of how your code might look:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/builders');

// Your bot token
const TOKEN = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

// Bot client
const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES] });

// Array containing the commands
const commands = [
  new SlashCommandBuilder()
    .setName('ban')
    .setDescription('Bans a user from the server')
    .toJSON(),
];

// REST API
const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(TOKEN);

// Uploading commands to Discord
(async () => {
  try {
    console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');
    await rest.put(
      Routes.applicationGuildCommands(client.application.id, 'YOUR_GUILD_ID'),
      { body: commands },
    );
    console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();

// Event listener for when the bot is ready
client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

// Event listener for when a message is created
client.on('messageCreate', async message => {
  if (!message.content.startsWith('//') || !message.content.startsWith('//ban')) {
    return;
  }

  const args = message.content.split(' ').slice(1);
  const target = message.mentions.users.first();

  if (!target) {
    return message.reply('Please mention a user to ban.');
  }

  if (message.author.id !== message.guild.ownerId && !message.member.hasPermission('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
    return message.reply('You do not have permission to use this command.');
  }

  const reason = args.slice(1).join(' ');

  try {
    await target.ban({ reason: reason || 'No reason provided' });
    message.reply(`Successfully banned ${target.tag}.`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    message.reply('There was an error trying to ban that user.');
  }
});

// Start the client
client.login(TOKEN);
```

Please replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` with your actual bot token and `'YOUR_GUILD_ID'` with the ID of the server where you want to use the bot.

Make sure to handle permissions and other edge cases as needed for your bot. This example assumes that the bot has the necessary permissions to ban users and that it is in a guild where it can execute this action.

Before running the bot, ensure you have the required dependencies installed:

```bash
npm install discord.js @discordjs/rest @discordjs/builders
```

Remember to follow Discord's terms of service and API usage guidelines when creating bots and using slash commands.

To convert a markdown string to HTML in C++, you can create a function that processes the input string according to basic markdown syntax rules. Here's a simple example that handles some common markdown elements like headings, italics, bold, and links. This example does not cover all possible markdown features but should give you a starting point.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Convert headings
    std::regex headingRegex("#+\\s*(.*)");
    std::string headingReplacement("<h$1>$2</h$1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, headingRegex, headingReplacement);

    // Convert italics
    std::regex italicRegex("_([^_]+)_");
    std::string italicReplacement("<em>$1</em>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicRegex, italicReplacement);

    // Convert bold
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*([^\\*]+)\\*");
    std::string boldReplacement("<strong>$1</strong>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, boldRegex, boldReplacement);

    // Convert links
    std::regex linkRegex("\\[([^\\]]+)\\]\\(([^\\)]+)\\)");
    std::string linkReplacement("<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, linkRegex, linkReplacement);

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Header\nThis is an _italic_ text. This is a **bold** text. Visit [example.com](http://example.com).";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHTML(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This program defines a `markdownToHTML` function that uses `std::regex` to find and replace markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags. The `main` function demonstrates how to use this function with a sample markdown string.

Remember, this is a basic implementation. For more comprehensive markdown-to-HTML conversion, consider using existing libraries like [cpp-markdown](https://github.com/progsource/cpp-markdown) or [cmark](https://github.com/commonmark/cmark) which provide extensive support for the markdown specification.

